{"post_stream":{"posts":[{"id":3400045,"name":"Ryan Reed","username":"Ryan_Reed","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/ryan_reed/{size}/268514_2.png","created_at":"2024-06-19T06:25:29.658Z","cooked":"

Quick preface: this is not a guide on crimping, just providing a cheap alternative to the official Molex SL crimp tool for teams who don’t have one, who just want to have a spare in case theirs breaks or gets lost (two is one, one is none) or for for training purposes.

There are images in the linked Printables post.

You will need:
1x IWISS SN-2549 Crimp Tool
1x printed positioner (linked here)
1x 20mm M4 screw
1x M4 nut
(optional) 1x M4 washer

Print the “IWISS_SN-2549_Positioner_for_Molex_SL.step” file using your material of choice. I recommend a material that is easy to print small features accurately with, like PLA. Mechanical properties of the material shouldn’t matter. You may want to enable the “external perimeters first” option in your slicer to make the holes slightly more accurate (this usually comes at the cost of overhang performance, but there are no overhangs here.)

With the jaws closed, remove the M4 screw from the bottom jaw of the SN-2549 crimp tool. Replace with a longer 20mm M4 screw. Ensure the jaws are still aligned and the crimp tool can still fully close. Place the positioner on the crimp tool with the protruding M4 screw in the large hole, and align the small holes on the printed positioner with the 3 main cavities on the crimp tool and secure with an M4 nut. The ridge on the positioner should help with alignment.

If the contacts are too loose or too tight, you may be to adjust the size of the holes using an option in your slicer. This should not be necessary but is an option to compensate for other issues. You may need to enable advanced options in your slicer before this setting will be visible.

In PrusaSlicer and some derivatives, this is XY Size Compensation under Advanced → Slicing.

In Bambu Studio this is XY Hole compensation under Quality-> Precision.

Since this is a STEP file, it is relatively easy to modify to fit other similar crimp tools. If you do modify the design please do not remove 3647 from the model without permission.

I also designed a part for use with a FS-D5T automatic wire stripper to consistently strip the perfect length for Molex SL contacts (linked here). The tool can be purchased for about $14 from Aliexpress or about $32 on eBay. If you are having trouble finding the part because search is awful, you can try searching by image. I tried a couple different cheap wire stripper guns, but this seemed to do the best (of the cheap ones, you can buy a nice one from McMaster-Carr for $80 that should work great out of the box) without modification. The part is to replace the included wire stop, which has a minimum strip length that is too long. This is also pretty easy to modify if you want to make the minimum strip length even shorter for other contacts.

strip the perfect length for Molex SL contacts

“strip the perfect length for Molex SL contacts” - what is your target strip length?

I really like this approach - a lot of these crimpers are cheap enough that you can do something like this to dedicate them to a specific use - this is a great idea.

I’ve had pretty good success with the Iwiss 3220 crimper for Molex SL terminations but I’ll check this out as well. It’s probably 75% over here that I already have this crimper in my ongoing search for the “perfect” crimper for whatever terminal.

I’ve been doing 4mm strip length, which appears to be longer than Molex’s prescribed 2.54-3.17mm. An easy parameter to modify though if you find it too long. 4mm strip length gives 1mm bare wire on both sides of the conductor crimp.

zog:

a lot of these crimpers are cheap enough that you can do something like this to dedicate them to a specific use

Yeah we have two of these specific tools, and just leave one with this on there. It is pretty easy to remove if the positioner is getting in the way for another contact, you just have to remove the nut. Aligning the holes up again to put it back on is pretty easy, only one degree of freedom due to the ridge that slides along the edge of the painted surface.

The IWISS 3220 looks like it would be more difficult to modify this way, but the jaws look very similar.

EDIT: The wires in the photos on the Printables post for the positioner were stripped with the FS-D5T and modified length stop (4mm).

Printables.com

IWISS 322M Terminal Positioner for Molex CLIK-Mate 1.5mm Terminals by...

This adapter holds the terminal and supports the blade of the terminal so the crimper doesn't bend it. | Download free 3D printable STL models

You could definitely mash the two models together with a couple boolean operations, and they were nice enough to provide the STEP file.
